                                <p>India's diverse population presents unique challenges in clinical cardiology, with varying patterns of heart diseases across different regions and communities. Rural areas, for instance, face a double burden of communicable and non-communicable diseases, while urban centers grapple with lifestyle-related cardiac conditions. The rapid economic growth and urbanization in India have led to lifestyle shifts that contribute to the escalation of cardiovascular risk factors, including hypertension, diabetes, obesity, and dyslipidemia. These risk factors, coupled with high levels of stress, smoking, and sedentary lifestyles, have accelerated the onset of heart diseases at younger ages compared to Western countries.</p>
                
